\highlight1\fs32 1. What are the key differences between Procedural Programming and ObjectOrientedProgramming (OOP)?\par
\par
\highlight0\fs22 | Procedural Programming             | Object-Oriented Programming           |\par
| ---------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |\par
| Based on procedures/functions      | Based on objects/classes              |\par
| Uses top-down design               | Uses bottom-up design                 |\par
| Data and functions are separate    | Data and functions are combined       |\par
| Less secure                        | More secure due to data hiding        |\par
| Difficult to manage large programs | Easier to manage large programs       |\par
| No inheritance or polymorphism     | Supports inheritance and polymorphism |\par
| Focuses on algorithm/process       | Focuses on real-world objects         |\par
Theoretical Difference Between Procedural Programming and OOP\par
Procedural Programming\par
Procedural Programming is a programming paradigm based on the concept of procedures or functions.\par
The program is divided into small functions, and these functions operate on data.\par
\par
It follows a top-down approach.\par
\par
Importance is given to functions and sequence of actions.\par
\par
Data is generally shared among functions.\par
\par
Suitable for small and medium-sized programs.\par
\par
Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)\par
Object-Oriented Programming is a programming paradigm based on the concept of objects and classes.\par
Objects contain both data and methods that operate on that data.\par
\par
It follows a bottom-up approach.\par
\par
Importance is given to objects and data security.\par
\par
Data is hidden using encapsulation.\par
\par
Suitable for large and complex software systems.\par
\par
Key Theoretical Differences\par
Procedural Programming\tab Object-Oriented Programming\par
Based on procedures/functions\tab Based on objects/classes\par
Uses top-down design\tab Uses bottom-up design\par
Data and functions are separate\tab Data and functions are combined\par
Less secure\tab More secure due to data hiding\par
Difficult to manage large programs\tab Easier to manage large programs\par
No inheritance or polymorphism\tab Supports inheritance and polymorphism\par
Focuses on algorithm/process\tab Focuses on real-world objects\par
Conclusion\par
Procedural Programming focuses on how the task is performed, whereas OOP focuses on objects that perform the task. OOP provides better security, reusability, and scalability compared to procedural programming.\par
\par
\highlight1\fs36 2. List and explain the main advantages of OOP over POP.\par
\par
\highlight0\fs22 Advantages of OOP over POP\par
\par
Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) offers several advantages over Procedural-Oriented Programming (POP):\par
\par
1. Data Security\par
\par
OOP provides encapsulation and data hiding, which protect data from unauthorized access.\par
In POP, data is usually global and less secure.\par
\par
2. Code Reusability\par
\par
OOP supports inheritance, allowing existing classes to be reused in new programs.\par
This reduces duplication of code and saves development time.\par
\par
3. Easy Maintenance\par
\par
Programs in OOP are organized into objects and classes, making large programs easier to manage, debug, and update.\par
\par
4. Modularity\par
\par
Each object works independently, so changes in one part of the program do not greatly affect other parts.\par
\par
5. Real-World Modeling\par
\par
OOP represents real-world entities using objects, making programs more realistic and easier to understand.\par
\par
6. Flexibility through Polymorphism\par
\par
The same function can perform different tasks depending on the object, increasing flexibility in programming.\par
\par
7. Better Scalability\par
\par
OOP is suitable for developing large and complex applications because new features can be added easily.\par
\par
8. Reduced Complexity\par
\par
By using abstraction, OOP hides unnecessary implementation details and shows only essential features.\par
\par
\par
