\highlight1\fs36 6. Explain the difference between implicit and explicit type conversion in C++.\line\par
\highlight0\f0\fs22\lang9 Difference Between Implicit and Explicit Type Conversion in C++\par
\par
Type conversion means converting one data type into another data type.\par
\par
There are two types of type conversion in C++:\par
\par
Implicit Type Conversion\par
Explicit Type Conversion\par
1. Implicit Type Conversion\par
\par
Implicit conversion is performed automatically by the compiler without programmer intervention.\par
\par
Also called automatic type conversion.\par
Usually converts smaller data types into larger data types to avoid data loss.\par
Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    int a = 10;\par
    float b = a;   // int automatically converted to float\par
\par
    cout << b;\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Output\par
10\par
Features\par
Done automatically by the compiler\par
No special syntax required\par
Safe when converting smaller types to larger types\par
2. Explicit Type Conversion\par
\par
Explicit conversion is performed manually by the programmer using casting operators.\par
\par
Also called type casting.\par
Used when the programmer wants to force conversion.\par
Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    float x = 5.8;\par
\par
    int y = (int)x;   // explicit conversion\par
\par
    cout << y;\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Output\par
5\par
Features\par
Done manually by the programmer\par
Uses casting operators like (int), (float)\par
May cause data loss\par
Key Differences\par
Implicit Conversion\tab Explicit Conversion\par
Done automatically by compiler\tab Done manually by programmer\par
No casting syntax needed\tab Requires type casting\par
Safer conversion\tab May lose data\par
Converts compatible types automatically\tab Forces conversion between types.\par
\par
