\highlight2\fs36 8  . Explain the purpose and use of constants and literals in C++.\par
\highlight0\fs22 Constants and Literals in C++\par
\par
Constants and literals are fixed values used in a C++ program. Their values do not change during program execution.\par
\par
Constants\par
\par
A constant is a named value whose value cannot be changed once assigned.\par
\par
Constants are declared using the const keyword.\par
\par
Syntax\par
const data_type variable_name = value;\par
Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    const int MAX = 100;\par
\par
    cout << MAX;\par
\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Purpose of Constants\par
Prevent accidental modification of values\par
Improve readability of the program\par
Make programs easier to maintain\par
Used for fixed values such as PI, tax rates, limits, etc.\par
Literals\par
\par
Literals are fixed values written directly in the program code.\par
\par
Types of Literals in C++\par
Type of Literal\tab Example\par
Integer Literal\tab 10, 25\par
Floating Literal\tab 3.14, 7.5\par
Character Literal\tab 'A', 'b'\par
String Literal\tab "Hello"\par
Boolean Literal\tab true, false\par
Example\par
int age = 18;\par
float marks = 85.5;\par
char grade = 'A';\par
\par
Here:\par
\par
18\par
85.5\par
'A'\par
\par
are literals.\par
\par
Difference Between Constants and Literals\par
Constants\tab Literals\par
Have names\tab Written directly in code\par
Declared using const\tab No declaration needed\par
Cannot be modified\tab Represent fixed values\par
Example: const int x = 5;\tab Example: 5.\par
\par
\highlight2\fs36 9. Difference Between for, while, and do-while Loops in C++\par
\highlight0\fs22\par
Loops are used to execute a block of code repeatedly in C++.\par
\par
The three main loops are:\par
\par
for loop\par
while loop\par
do-while loop\par
1. for Loop\par
\par
The for loop is used when the number of iterations is known in advance.\par
\par
Syntax\par
for(initialization; condition; update) \{\par
    // code\par
\}\par
Example\par
for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) \{\par
    cout << i;\par
\}\par
\par
\highlight2\fs36 10. How are break and continue statements used in loops? Provide \par
\highlight0\fs22 1. break Statement\par
\par
The break statement is used to immediately terminate a loop or switch statement.\par
\par
When break is encountered, control moves outside the loop.\par
\par
Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) \{\par
        if(i == 3) \{\par
            break;\par
        \}\par
        cout << i << " ";\par
    \}\par
\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Output\par
1 2\par
Explanation\par
The loop stops when i becomes 3.\par
Remaining iterations are not executed.\par
2. continue Statement\par
\par
The continue statement skips the current iteration and moves to the next iteration of the loop.\par
\par
Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) \{\par
        if(i == 3) \{\par
            continue;\par
        \}\par
        cout << i << " ";\par
    \}\par
\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Output\par
1 2 4 5\par
Explanation\par
When i becomes 3, that iteration is skipped.\par
The loop continues with the next value.\par
Difference Between break and continue\par
break\tab continue\par
Terminates the loop completely\tab Skips only the current iteration\par
Control exits the loop\tab Control goes to next iteration\par
Used to stop looping\tab Used to skip specific conditions.\par
\highlight2\fs36 11. Explain nested control structures with an example.\par
\highlight0\fs22 Nested Control Structures in C++\par
\par
A nested control structure means placing one control structure inside another control structure.\par
\par
Examples:\par
\par
An if statement inside another if\par
A loop inside another loop\par
An if statement inside a loop\par
\par
Nested structures are used when multiple conditions or repeated operations are required.\par
\par
Nested if Statement Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    int age = 20;\par
    int marks = 75;\par
\par
    if(age >= 18) \{\par
        if(marks >= 50) \{\par
            cout << "Eligible";\par
        \}\par
    \}\par
\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Explanation\par
The first if checks the age.\par
The second if inside it checks the marks.\par
Output is displayed only if both conditions are true.\par
Nested Loop Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    for(int i = 1; i <= 3; i++) \{\par
        for(int j = 1; j <= 2; j++) \{\par
            cout << i << " " << j << endl;\par
        \}\par
    \}\par
\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Output\par
1 1\par
1 2\par
2 1\par
2 2\par
3 1\par
3 2\par
Explanation\par
The outer loop runs 3 times.\par
For each iteration of the outer loop, the inner loop runs 2 times.\par
Uses of Nested Control Structures\par
Pattern printing\par
Matrix operations\par
Multi-condition checking\par
Menu-driven programs\par
\highlight2\fs36 12. What is a function in C++? Explain the concept of function declaration, definition, and calling.\par
\par
\highlight0\fs22 Function in C++\par
\par
A function is a block of code that performs a specific task. Functions help divide a program into smaller and manageable parts, making the code reusable and easier to understand.\par
\par
Concepts of Functions in C++\par
\par
There are three important parts of a function:\par
\par
Function Declaration\par
Function Definition\par
Function Calling\par
1. Function Declaration\par
\par
A function declaration tells the compiler about:\par
\par
function name\par
return type\par
parameters\par
\par
It is also known as a function prototype.\par
\par
Syntax\par
return_type function_name(parameters);\par
Example\par
int add(int, int);\par
\par
This statement informs the compiler that a function named add exists and returns an integer value.\par
\par
2. Function Definition\par
\par
The function definition contains the actual code that performs the task.\par
\par
Syntax\par
return_type function_name(parameters) \{\par
    // function body\par
\}\par
Example\par
int add(int a, int b) \{\par
    return a + b;\par
\}\par
\par
Here:\par
\par
a and b are parameters\par
return a + b; returns the sum\par
3. Function Calling\par
\par
Function calling means executing the function using its name.\par
\par
Example\par
int result = add(5, 3);\par
\par
Here:\par
\par
5 and 3 are arguments passed to the function\par
The function executes and returns the result\par
Complete Program Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
// Function Declaration\par
int add(int, int);\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    // Function Calling\par
    int result = add(5, 3);\par
\par
    cout << "Sum = " << result;\par
\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
\par
// Function Definition\par
int add(int a, int b) \{\par
    return a + b;\par
\}\par
Output\par
Sum = 8\par
Advantages of Functions\par
Reusability of code\par
Reduces repetition\par
Easier debugging\par
Improves readability and maintenance.\par
\par
\highlight2\fs32 13.  Explain recursion in C++ with an example.\par
\highlight0\fs22 Scope of Variables in C++\par
\par
The scope of a variable refers to the region of a program where the variable can be accessed or used.\par
\par
In C++, variables mainly have two types of scope:\par
\par
Local Scope\par
Global Scope\par
1. Local Scope\par
\par
A variable declared inside a function or block is called a local variable.\par
\par
It can be accessed only within that function or block.\par
It is created when the function starts and destroyed when the function ends.\par
Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
void display() \{\par
    int x = 10;   // local variable\par
    cout << x;\par
\}\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    display();\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Explanation\par
x is local to the display() function.\par
It cannot be accessed outside the function.\par
2. Global Scope\par
\par
A variable declared outside all functions is called a global variable.\par
\par
It can be accessed from any function in the program.\par
It remains in memory throughout the program execution.\par
Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int x = 20;   // global variable\par
\par
void display() \{\par
    cout << x;\par
\}\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    display();\par
    cout << x;\par
\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Explanation\par
x is accessible inside both display() and main() functions.\par
Difference Between Local and Global Scope\par
Local Scope\tab Global Scope\par
Declared inside a function/block\tab Declared outside all functions\par
Accessible only within that block\tab Accessible throughout the program\par
Exists for a limited time\tab Exists during entire program execution\par
More secure\tab Less secure due to wider access.\par
\highlight2\fs40 14.  What are function prototypes in C++? Why are they used?\par
\highlight0\fs22 Function Prototypes in C++\par
\par
A function prototype is a declaration of a function that tells the compiler:\par
\par
the function name\par
return type\par
number and type of parameters\par
\par
It informs the compiler about the function before its actual definition.\par
\par
Syntax of Function Prototype\par
return_type function_name(parameter_list);\par
\cf3\highlight4\fs52 5. Arrays and Strings\par
\par
\cf4\highlight2\fs36 15 . Explain string handling in C++ with examples. \par
\par
\highlight0\fs22 String Handling in C++\par
\par
A string in C++ is a sequence of characters used to store text such as names, sentences, or messages.\par
\par
C++ provides two ways to handle strings:\par
\par
Character arrays (char)\par
string class from the standard library\par
\par
The string class is easier and more commonly used.\par
\par
To use strings, include the header file:\par
\par
#include <string>\par
Declaring and Initializing Strings\par
Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
#include <string>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    string name = "John";\par
\par
    cout << name;\par
\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Common String Operations\par
1. Input and Output of Strings\par
Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
#include <string>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    string name;\par
\par
    cin >> name;\par
\par
    cout << name;\par
\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
2. Concatenation of Strings\par
\par
Strings can be joined using the + operator.\par
\par
Example\par
string first = "Hello";\par
string second = "World";\par
\par
string result = first + " " + second;\par
