\highlight2\fs36 16.How are arrays initialized 3. How are arrays initialized in C++? Provide examples of both 1D and 2D arrays.\par
\par
\highlight0\fs22 Array Initialization in C++\par
\par
Array initialization means assigning values to array elements at the time of declaration.\par
\par
Arrays can be initialized in different ways in C++.\par
\par
1D (One-Dimensional) Array Initialization\par
\par
A one-dimensional array stores elements in a single row.\par
\par
Syntax\par
data_type array_name[size] = \{values\};\par
Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    int numbers[5] = \{10, 20, 30, 40, 50\};\par
\par
    for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) \{\par
        cout << numbers[i] << " ";\par
    \}\par
\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Output\par
10 20 30 40 50\par
Partial Initialization of 1D Array\par
\par
If fewer values are provided, remaining elements become 0.\par
\par
Example\par
int arr[5] = \{1, 2\};\par
\par
Result:\par
\par
1 2 0 0 0\par
2D (Two-Dimensional) Array Initialization\par
\par
A two-dimensional array stores data in rows and columns like a matrix.\par
\par
Syntax\par
data_type array_name[rows][columns] = \{\par
    \{values\},\par
    \{values\}\par
\};\par
Example\par
#include <iostream>\par
using namespace std;\par
\par
int main() \{\par
    int matrix[2][3] = \{\par
        \{1, 2, 3\},\par
        \{4, 5, 6\}\par
    \};\par
\par
    for(int i = 0; i < 2; i++) \{\par
        for(int j = 0; j < 3; j++) \{\par
            cout << matrix[i][j] << " ";\par
        \}\par
    \}\par
\par
    return 0;\par
\}\par
Output\par
1 2 3 4 5 6\par
Difference Between 1D and 2D Array Initialization\par
1D Array\tab 2D Array\par
Uses one index\tab Uses two indices\par
Stores data in linear form\tab Stores data in table form\par
Example: int a[5]=\{1,2,3\};\tab Example: int a[2][2]=\{\{1,2\},\{3,4\}\};\line\par
